#TRN               !transport model specification
ECS  Extended Corresponding States model (C12 reference); fit to data.
?LITERATURE REFERENCES \
?Huber, M.L., Laesecke, A., and Perkins, R.A., Model for the viscosity
? and thermal conductivity of refrigerants, including a new correlation
? for the viscosity of R134a, Ind.Eng.Chem.Res. 42: 3163-3178 (2003).
?\
?DATA SOURCES FOR VISCOSITY\
?The parameters for viscosity were based on the data of:\
?
?Dymond, J.H., Young, K.J.(1980b). "Transport Properties of
? Nonelectrolyte Liquid Mixtures- I. Viscosity Coefficients
? for n-Alkane Mixtures at Saturation Pressure from 283 to 378K"
? Int. J. Thermophys. 1(4):331-344.
?
?Average absolute deviations of the fit from the experimental data were:
?   Dymond: avg 2.5% (max 5.1)
? Overall: 2.5%
?
?DATA SOURCES FOR THERMAL CONDUCTIVITY\
?The parameters for thermal conductivity were based on the data of:\
?
?Sakiadis, B.C., Coates, J., "Studies of the Thermal Conductivity of Liquids",
? Pts. I and II, AIChE J, 1:275-288 (1955).
?
?Bogatov, G.F., Rastorguev, Yu. L., and Grigor'ev, B.A., "Thermal conductivity of normal
? hydrocarbons at high temperatures and pressures", Khim. i Tekh. Topliv i Masel,9:31-33 (1969)
?
?Average absolute deviations of the fit from the experimental data were:
?   Sakiadis: avg 2.46% (max -2.46), Bogatov: avg 4.28% (max 6.1)
?   Overall: 4.2%
?
?The Lennard-Jones parameters are estimated using the method of Chung.\
?\
!end of info section
291.34             !lower temperature limit [K]
1000.              !upper temperature limit [K]
100000.            !upper pressure limit [kPa]
10.                !maximum density [mol/L]
FEQ c12.fld
VS1                !model for reference fluid viscosity
TC1                !model for reference fluid thermal conductivity
1                  !Lennard-Jones flag (0 or 1) (0 => use estimates)
0.8175             !Lennard-Jones coefficient sigma [nm] for ECS method
573.41             !Lennard-Jones coefficient epsilon/kappa [K] for ECS method
1  0  0            !number of terms in f_int term in Eucken correlation, spare1, spare 2
 1.3200d-3      0.0   0.0   0.0  !coeff, power of T, spare 1, spare 2
2  0  0                          !number of terms in psi (visc shape factor): poly,spare1,spare2
  1.1084400     0.0   0.0   0.0  !coeff, power of Tr, power of Dr, spare
  -3.47091d-02  0.0   1.0   0.0  !coeff, power of Tr, power of Dr, spare
2  0  0                          !number of terms in phi (thermal cond. shape factor): poly,spare1,spare2
   0.9728440    0.0   0.0   0.0  !coeff, power of Tr, power of Dr, spare
   2.83155d-02  0.0   1.0   0.0  !coeff, power of Tr, power of Dr, spare
TK3                !pointer to critical enhancement auxiliary function


#AUX               !thermal conductivity critical enhancement model
TK3  simplified thermal conductivity critical enhancement of Olchowy and Sengers
?LITERATURE REFERENCE \
?Olchowy, G.A. and Sengers, J.V.,
? "A simplified representation for the thermal conductivity of fluids in the
? critical region,"
? Int. J. Thermophysics, 10:417-426, 1989.
?\
?as applied to CO2 by:
?\
?Vesovic, V., Wakeham, W.A., Olchowy, G.A., Sengers, J.V., Watson, J.T.R.
? and Millat, J.,
? "The transport properties of carbon dioxide,"
? J. Phys. Chem. Ref. Data, 19:763-808, 1990.
?\
!end of info section
291.34             !lower temperature limit [K]
1000.              !upper temperature limit [K]
100000.            !upper pressure limit [kPa]
10.00              !maximum density [mol/L]
9  0  0  0         !# terms:  CO2-terms, spare, spare, spare
1.0     1.0     1.0      !reducing par for T, rho, tcx (mW/m-K)
0.630d0            !gnu (universal exponent)
1.239d0            !gamma (universal exponent)
1.03d0             !R0 (universal amplitude)
0.063d0            !z (universal exponent--not used for t.c., only viscosity)
